MATERIAL: Sundevall, in his brief original description (1850: 107) gave no indication that he had more than a single specimen at hand. His acquisition catalogue, however, shows that there were two skins available. 
<bibRefCitation author="Gyldenstolpe, N." box="[151,479,799,826]" pageId="27" pageNumber="548" pagination="1 - 116" refId="ref28755" refString="Gyldenstolpe, N. (1926) Types of birds in the Royal Natural History Museum in Stockholm. Arkiv f or Zoologi, 19, 1 - 116." type="journal article" year="1926">Gyldenstolpe (1926: 68–69)</bibRefCitation>
referred to NRM 569780 [7076] as a “type”, here treated as a 
<typeStatus box="[1188,1296,799,825]" pageId="27" pageNumber="548">lectotype</typeStatus>
designation of this study skin of a male collected 
<date box="[585,812,835,861]" pageId="27" pageNumber="548" value="1841-11-18">
<collectingDate box="[585,812,835,861]" pageId="27" pageNumber="548" value="1841-11-18">18 November 1841</collectingDate>
</date>
at Magaliesberg. The 
<typeStatus box="[1072,1233,835,861]" pageId="27" pageNumber="548">paralectotype</typeStatus>
, NRM 90144785 [7077], is a female collected 
<date box="[492,715,871,897]" pageId="27" pageNumber="548" value="1841-12-11">
<collectingDate box="[492,715,871,897]" pageId="27" pageNumber="548" value="1841-12-11">11 December 1841</collectingDate>
</date>
at Magaliesberg
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
